# Error paths and logging

## Rule

Changing an error path must preserve operator diagnostics, user-safe messaging,
metrics, and cleanup behavior.

## Checklist

1. Before narrowing a catch block or adding an early throw, read the existing
   error path end-to-end.
2. Preserve logs, trace IDs, metadata, metrics, and structured error fields.
3. Use shared API-error extraction helpers for user-visible messages.
4. Do not leak secrets, tokens, connection strings, or private payloads in logs.
5. Keep callback semantics distinct: `onSuccess`, `onInfo`, `onWarning`, and
   `onError` should not be reused for a different severity.
6. If an error path changes retry behavior, verify idempotency and backoff.
7. If a fallback is removed, document why it is no longer needed and update tests.

## Pre-commit check

- [ ] Existing logs/metrics are preserved or intentionally replaced.
- [ ] Cleanup still runs on every failure path.
- [ ] User-facing messages are safe and helpful.
- [ ] Tests cover the new failure branch.
